ðŸŽ¯ Goal of Day 2

By the end of today, you will have:

âœ… Clean data loaded from CSV
âœ… Converted text â†’ numbers
âœ… Created:

double[][] X (features)

double[] y (target)

This is the exact format we need for training ML models tomorrow (Day 3).

ðŸ§  THEORY (Short but Strong)
1) Why Preprocessing?

Because ML models are like calculators.

If you give them:

"20" (string)

"2" (string)

They canâ€™t do math.

So we convert to:

20.0

2.0

2) Features vs Target

From your student dataset:

Features (X):

age

study_hours

Target (y):

marks

ðŸ›  PRACTICAL (Windows + Smile 2.6.0)
âœ… Step 1 â€” Make sure CSV has NO header

Your students.csv should be like:

Ravi,20,2,45
Priya,21,5,78
Aman,19,1,30
Neha,22,6,88
Rahul,20,3,60
Sneha,21,4,72

âœ… Step 2 â€” Create Day2Preprocessing.java

Create this file:

src/main/java/com/darling/ai/Day2Preprocessing.java


Paste this code:

package com.darling.ai;

import smile.data.DataFrame;
import smile.io.Read;

import java.net.URL;
import java.nio.file.Paths;

public class Day2Preprocessing {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {

        // 1) Load CSV from resources
        URL resource = Day2Preprocessing.class
                .getClassLoader()
                .getResource("data/students.csv");

        if (resource == null) {
            throw new RuntimeException("students.csv not found in src/main/resources/data/");
        }

        var path = Paths.get(resource.toURI());
        DataFrame df = Read.csv(path);

        System.out.println("=== Raw Dataset Preview ===");
        System.out.println(df.slice(0, 6));

        // 2) Convert DataFrame -> X and y
        int n = df.nrows();

        // Features: age, study_hours
        double[][] X = new double[n][2];

        // Target: marks
        double[] y = new double[n];

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {

            // Smile 2.6.0 reads columns as V1, V2, V3, V4
            // V1 = name
            // V2 = age
            // V3 = study_hours
            // V4 = marks

            String ageStr = df.getString(i, 1);
            String hoursStr = df.getString(i, 2);
            String marksStr = df.getString(i, 3);

            double age = Double.parseDouble(ageStr.trim());
            double hours = Double.parseDouble(hoursStr.trim());
            double marks = Double.parseDouble(marksStr.trim());

            X[i][0] = age;
            X[i][1] = hours;
            y[i] = marks;
        }

        // 3) Print to confirm conversion
        System.out.println("\n=== Converted Numeric Data ===");
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            System.out.println("Row " + i +
                    " -> age=" + X[i][0] +
                    ", hours=" + X[i][1] +
                    " | marks=" + y[i]);
        }
    }
}

âœ… Expected Output

You should see:

Row 0 -> age=20.0, hours=2.0 | marks=45.0
Row 1 -> age=21.0, hours=5.0 | marks=78.0
...
